Maintenance cost reduction through predictive techniques¶

BACKGROUND¶

A company has a fleet of devices transmitting daily telemetry readings. They would like to create a predictive maintenance solution to proactively identify when maintenance should be performed. This approach promises cost savings over routine or time-based preventive maintenance, because tasks are performed only when warranted.

GOAL¶

You are tasked with building a predictive model using machine learning to predict the probability of a device failure. When building this model, be sure to minimize false positives and false negatives. The column you are trying to predict is called failure with binary value 0 for non-failure and 1 for failure.

APPROACH¶

There are several ways to formulate a predictive maintenance problem:

  1. Binary classification: define a window leading up to failure where the probability is predicted
  2. Multi-class classification: define buckets of "time to failure" and predict those classes directly
  3. Regression: define "time to failure" as a continuous variable and predict that directly
  4. Unsupervised: use independent variables to identify anomalous behaviour which could indicate imminent failure

I opted for formulation #1 with a 30 day failure window because the goal specifies that probability of device failure should be predicted.

In a real world setting, the correct approach would depend on the business case for the model.
Questions I'd explore are:

  • How much advance notice is needed to service devices before failure occurs?
  • What is the cost of a false positive? What is the cost of a false negative?
  • How do maintenance decision makers prefer to view risk of a failure? How much justification is needed to make a decision?

RESULTS¶

Random forest was able to give extremely promising results (F1=0.98), producing a few false negatives and no false positives. Catboost (F1=0.83) was the runner up while logistic regression (F1=0.07) was largely ineffective. Metrics 6, 1, and 5 seem to be the most predictive of failure.

RECOMMENDATION¶

I would propose the random forest model to business stakeholders for use in predicting maintenance work. I would also recommend using an interpretability framework like SHAP to understand which of the sensors was most predictive of the upcoming failure, so service technicians have some insight into where the issues may lie.

While this RF model is being prototyped, I'd explore other methods or more intensive feature engineering techniques to arrive at a more robust model that may generalize better to unseen data. I would also set up a monitoring framework to ensure this model doesn't suffer from concept drift over time, and consider implementing a retraining cadence as we collect more telemetry data. This is a fairly small dataset, and we only evaluated on a test set of 26 failed devices. I would be cautious about using this model in a production setting to make business decisions until we do more exhaustive cross validtion or evaluate the model on more unseen device failures.

# Define a time to failure column so we can generate a target variable within a window of failure time (30 days)
fail_dates = df.query("failure == 1")[['device', 'date']].rename(columns={'date': 'fail_date'})
features = features.merge(fail_dates, how='left', on='device')
features['time_to_failure'] = features.fail_date - features.date
features['fail_in_30d'] = (features.time_to_failure.dt.days <= 30).astype(int)
features[features.fail_date.notnull()].head()

Feature engineering¶

Based on the sensor spikes we saw leading up to failures, let's use differencing and rolling window features to give the model more signal

# Generate difference features - validate hypotehsis that most failures happen after a spike/dip in the metrics
metric_features = features.drop(columns=['failure', 'fail_date', 'time_to_failure', 'fail_in_30d', 'date'])
diff_features = metric_features.groupby('device').diff().fillna(0)
diff_features.columns = [x + '_diff' for x in diff_features.columns]
features = features.merge(diff_features, left_index=True, right_index=True)

In [21]:
# Generate rolling std dev features - use rolling window sizes learned from above distributions
# 50th & 75th quantiles should capture most metric spikes that correlate with failures
quantile = '50%'
rolling_features = []
for metric in diff_features.columns:   
    window_size = diff_stats.T.query("feature == @metric")[quantile].dt.days.values[0]
    rolling_feature = features[['device'] + diff_features.columns.tolist()].groupby('device')[metric].rolling(window_size, min_periods=1).std().fillna(0)
    rolling_feature.name = rolling_feature.name + '_roll_std_' + str(window_size)
    rolling_features.append(rolling_feature)
    
rolling_features = pd.concat(rolling_features, axis=1)
features = features.reset_index(drop=True)
rolling_features = rolling_features.reset_index(drop=True)
features = features.merge(rolling_features, left_index=True, right_index=True)

# Do custom train test split so we can ensure the entire time series for a device stays intact
fails = all_devices[all_devices == 1]
no_fails = all_devices[all_devices == 0]
seed = 42

# Use stratified sampling so the balance of failures is simlar across both sets, using roughly a 70/30 split
train_devices = no_fails.sample(800, random_state=seed).index.tolist() + fails.sample(80, random_state=seed).index.tolist()
test_devices = no_fails.sample(263, random_state=seed).index.tolist() + fails.sample(26, random_state=seed).index.tolist()

In [136]:
# Define a function to comprehensively evaluate models
# We use precision-recall curve rather than ROC because of the imbalanced dataset
def evaluate(pipe, preds, y_test, X_test, plot=True):
    print("Predicted positives:", preds.sum(), "Actual positives:", y_test.sum())
    print("Confusion matrix")
    print(pd.DataFrame(confusion_matrix(y_test, preds)))
    print(classification_report(y_test, preds, digits=5))
    if plot:
        plot_precision_recall_curve(pipe, X_test, y_test)

Experimenting with non-linear methods¶

It seems that a simple logistic regression will not be the ideal model for this use case.
I suspect tree based methods will perform better because the sensors indicate failure when they spike above a certain threshold, which trees can capture well.
I will start with catboost because it trains quickly and requires less tuning than other gradient boosted methods.

Balancing false positives & false negatives¶

The catboost classifier is doing much better than logistic, but it's skewed to predict more false negatives, presumably due to the class imbalance.
One technique for handling this is oversampling. I prefer to use SMOTE because it gives the model new synthetic samples to learn from.

In [239]:
smote = SMOTE(random_state=seed)
X_res, y_res = smote.fit_resample(X, y)
print(X_res.shape)

cb = CatBoostClassifier(iterations=1000, learning_rate=0.03, loss_function='Logloss', reg_lambda=5,
                        verbose=False, random_seed=seed, has_time=True)
cb.fit(X_res, y_res)
preds = cb.predict(test[feature_set])

evaluate(cb, preds, y_test, X_test)
# Model: Catboost with oversampling
# Result: Small hit to F1 score. More true positives, but at the expense of significantly more false positives.

Threshold tuning¶

SMOTE helped to an extent, but the F1 score took a hit. I think we can have even better performance by adjusting the threshold for classifying a failure.
I'll use precision & recall to identify a threshold which will give us an optimal F1 score and use that to generate predictions.

In [240]:
cb = CatBoostClassifier(iterations=1000, learning_rate=0.03, loss_function='Logloss', reg_lambda=5,
                        verbose=False, random_seed=seed, has_time=True)
cb.fit(X, y)
preds = cb.predict_proba(test[feature_set])[:, 1]
precision, recall, thresholds = precision_recall_curve(y_test, preds)

# convert to f score
fscore = (2 * precision * recall) / (precision + recall)
# locate the index of the largest f score
ix = np.argmax(fscore)
print('Best Threshold=%f, F-Score=%.3f' % (thresholds[ix], fscore[ix]))
Out[240]:
<catboost.core.CatBoostClassifier at 0x298df489f70>
Best Threshold=0.183521, F-Score=0.834
In [241]:
preds = (preds > thresholds[ix]).astype(int)
evaluate(cb, preds, y_test, X_test, plot=False)
# Model: Catboost with threshold tuning
# Result: Marginally better F1 performance and much better balance of FP & FN

Analyze results¶

The threshold tuning gave significant lift in all metrics. It both classifies more true positives and gives a very balanced FN/FP rate.
In a real business setting, we would use a cost matrix to further optimize the balance of FP & FN. It's possible that a false negative is more costly to the business because it will result in a device failing unexpectedly and causing an outage. Whereas a false positive just means a device will get serviced earlier than it needs to.

In order to see our classifier performance more tangibly, I will plot the failure probabilities for every device in the test set so we can see if they gradually increase 30 days before a failure like we'd expect.

In [244]:

plot.axhline(y=thresholds[ix], color='b', linestyle='--')

Can we do even better?¶

It's possible that bagging would do a better job than boosting in this case because each tree can learn the failure thresholds for each device type.
Boosting would reduce errors of the residuals for a single tree and possibly create too complex of a decision boundary to perform well on a variety of devices.

In [225]:
rf = RandomForestClassifier(random_state=seed, n_jobs=-1)
rf.fit(X, y)
preds = rf.predict(test[feature_set])

evaluate(rf, preds, y_test, X_test)
# Model: out of box random forest
# Result: Nearly perfect performance, other than a few false negatives

We've arrived at an ideal model¶

Random forest performs better than catboost without any tuning! This model has much clearer separation between high & low probabilities, so maintenance decision makers can have more confidence in the preditions they see.
It seems that this model only suffers from a few false negatives, and all of them are for device W1F0X5GW where it flatlines in April just below the clssifier threshold.

As a final step, let's inspect the feature importances of the three models to see how much agreement there was between estimators and which features provided the most signal.

In [252]:
# Compare feature importances

Next steps¶

Given more time, I would want to explore deep learning techniques to better model the patterns which are predictive of failure. In this example, we did some very light feture engineering and were lucky enough to produce an accurate model, but I presume there is much more information packed in these metrics which could be better mined using sequence models such as LSTMs or transformers. Another approach would be to leverage a more exhaustive feature engineering framework like tsfresh or featuretools. I would also plan on using an interpretability framework like SHAP to better understand the features driving failure predictions at a local level.
